I'm reading the book "When Coffee and Kale Compete" and I'm trying to understand the concept of push and pull in the context of the Job To Be Done (JTBD) framework. Can someone explain what these terms mean and how they relate to the JTBD theory?
In the context of the Job To Be Done (JTBD) framework, "push" and "pull" are forces that influence a consumer's decision to switch from one product or solution to another. These concepts were introduced by Clayton Christensen, a Harvard Business School professor, as part of his theory on innovation and customer behavior.

1. Push:
The "push" refers to the problems or frustrations that a consumer experiences with their current solution or product. These negative aspects of the existing situation drive the consumer to consider switching to a new solution. The push can be caused by various factors, such as poor performance, high cost, inconvenience, or lack of desired features

To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor's VCC and GND pins should be connected to the Arduino's power and ground, respectively. The analog output pin of the LM35 should be connected to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The first pin of the potentiometer should be connected to +VCC, the second pin to pin 3 of the LCD, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

3. Install the necessary libraries in the Arduino IDE. Go to Tools > Manage Libraries, search for "LiquidCrystal I2C", and install the LiquidCrystal_I2C library by Frank de Brabander [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

4. Upload the code to your Arduino board. You can find sample code in the tutorials mentioned in the search results [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd), [2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd), [3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. To enable C++20 in Visual Studio, you can follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer.
2. Select "Properties" from the context menu.
3. In the Properties window, go to "Configuration Properties" > "C/C++" > "Language".
4. Set the "C++ Language Standard" option to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)".
5. Click "Apply" and then "OK" to save the changes.
